---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";
import { qatarCostOfLiving } from "../../data/qatar/cost-of-living";
import { buildBreadcrumbs, buildArticleSchema, buildFAQSchema } from "../../lib/seo";
import RelatedLinks from "../../components/ui/RelatedLinks.astro";
import SourcesBlock from "../../components/ui/SourcesBlock.astro";
import FAQAccordion from "../../components/ui/FAQAccordion.astro";
import CostOfLivingSimulator from "../../components/calculators/CostOfLivingSimulator";

const faqs = [
  { question: "How much does a single expat need to live in Doha in 2026?", answer: "A single expat in Doha needs approximately QAR 6,000-10,000 (~EUR 1,500-2,500) per month. This covers a one-bedroom apartment (QAR 3,500-5,500 (~EUR 875-1,375)), groceries (QAR 800-1,200 (~EUR 200-300)), transport (QAR 400-800 (~EUR 100-200)), dining out (QAR 600-1,200 (~EUR 150-300)), utilities (QAR 300-600 (~EUR 75-150)), and personal expenses (QAR 400-700 (~EUR 100-175)). Living in premium areas like The Pearl or West Bay pushes costs toward the higher end." },
  { question: "Is Qatar cheaper than Dubai for expats?", answer: "Yes, Doha is generally 15-25% cheaper than Dubai for comparable lifestyles. Housing is the largest difference: a one-bedroom in central Doha costs QAR 4,500-6,500 (~EUR 1,125-1,625) versus AED 6,000-10,000 (~EUR 1,500-2,500) in central Dubai. Qatar also has no VAT (the UAE charges 5%), which reduces everyday spending on groceries, dining, and services." },
  { question: "Does Qatar have VAT or sales tax?", answer: "No. As of 2026, Qatar does not impose VAT or any general sales tax. This is a meaningful cost advantage over the UAE (5% VAT) and Saudi Arabia (15% VAT). Prices at supermarkets, restaurants, and shops are final with no added tax at checkout." },
  { question: "How much do families spend on schooling in Qatar?", answer: "International school fees in Qatar range from QAR 20,000 (~EUR 5,000) to QAR 65,000 (~EUR 16,250) per year. Budget schools with Indian or Philippine curricula charge QAR 12,000-22,000 (~EUR 3,000-5,500). British and American curriculum schools cost QAR 30,000-50,000 (~EUR 7,500-12,500). Premium institutions like Doha College and the American School of Doha charge QAR 45,000-65,000 (~EUR 11,250-16,250). Many employers include education allowances in the benefits package." },
  { question: "What are utility costs like in Qatar?", answer: "Utility costs in Qatar are modest. Kahramaa (electricity and water) bills typically run QAR 300-800 (~EUR 75-200) per month for a standard apartment. Internet (Ooredoo or Vodafone Qatar) costs QAR 300-500 (~EUR 75-125) for home broadband. Mobile plans with data start at QAR 100 (~EUR 25). Air conditioning drives most of the electricity cost, particularly during the summer months from May to October." },
];

const breadcrumbs = [{ name: "Home", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/" }, { name: "Qatar", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/qatar/guide/" }, { name: "Cost of Living", url: "https://arabiaexpat.com/qatar/cost-of-living/" }];
---
<GuideLayout title="Qatar Cost of Living 2026: Doha Rent, Food & No VAT" description="Monthly budget Doha: QAR 6,500-9,500 single, QAR 15,000-25,000 family. Zero VAT saves 5-15% versus UAE and Saudi. Interactive cost simulator included." canonical="/qatar/cost-of-living/" schemas={[buildBreadcrumbs(breadcrumbs), buildArticleSchema("Qatar Cost of Living 2026: Rent, Food and Prices in Doha", "Detailed Qatar cost of living guide for 2026.", "https://arabiaexpat.com/qatar/cost-of-living/", "2025-01-15", "2026-06-01"), buildFAQSchema(faqs)]} breadcrumbs={[{ name: "Home", url: "/" }, { name: "Qatar", url: "/qatar/guide/" }, { name: "Cost of Living", url: "/qatar/cost-of-living/" }]}>

<div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-900 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 rounded-xl">
  <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3">Qatar VAT Savings Calculator</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">See how much Qatar's zero-VAT policy saves you compared to living in the UAE or Saudi Arabia.</p>
  <form id="vatCalc" class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
    <div>
      <label class="block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-1" for="vatSpend">Monthly spending on goods/services (QAR)</label>
      <input type="number" id="vatSpend" value="6000" min="1000" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 px-3 py-2 text-sm" />
    </div>
    <div>
      <label class="block text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-1" for="vatYears">Contract duration (years)</label>
      <select id="vatYears" class="w-full rounded-lg border border-gray-300 dark:border-gray-700 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 px-3 py-2 text-sm">
        <option value="1">1 year</option>
        <option value="2" selected>2 years</option>
        <option value="3">3 years</option>
        <option value="5">5 years</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="flex items-end">
      <button type="button" onclick="(function(){var s=parseInt(document.getElementById('vatSpend').value)||0,y=parseInt(document.getElementById('vatYears').value),uae5=s*0.05,ksa15=s*0.15,uaeTotal=uae5*12*y,ksaTotal=ksa15*12*y;document.getElementById('vatResult').innerHTML='<strong>Your Qatar zero-VAT savings:</strong><br><span class=\'text-xs\'>vs UAE (5%): QAR '+uaeTotal.toLocaleString()+' (~EUR '+(uaeTotal*0.25|0).toLocaleString()+') over '+y+' yr</span><br><span class=\'text-xs\'>vs Saudi (15%): QAR '+ksaTotal.toLocaleString()+' (~EUR '+(ksaTotal*0.25|0).toLocaleString()+') over '+y+' yr</span>';})();" class="w-full px-5 py-2.5 bg-teal-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-teal-700 transition-colors">Calculate Savings</button>
    </div>
    <div id="vatResult" class="sm:col-span-3 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 min-h-[2rem]"></div>
  </form>
</div>

<h1>Qatar Cost of Living in 2026: Doha Price Guide</h1>

<div class="not-prose mb-8">
<CostOfLivingSimulator client:visible defaultCity="doha" />
</div>

<p>Qatar occupies a unique financial position among Gulf states for expatriates. The country charges neither income tax on employment earnings nor value-added tax on goods and services, a combination that no other GCC nation offers. This twin-zero policy has a compounding effect on personal finances: every riyal you earn stays in your pocket, and every riyal you spend buys its full face value without any tax surcharge at the point of sale. For a professional earning QAR 15,000 per month and spending QAR 8,000 on living costs, the absence of VAT saves between QAR 400 and QAR 1,200 monthly depending on whether you compare against the UAE's 5% rate or Saudi Arabia's 15% rate. Over a standard two-year contract, that amounts to QAR 9,600 to QAR 28,800 in additional purchasing power that simply does not exist in neighboring countries.</p>

<p>Doha is the center of all economic activity in Qatar, and nearly every expatriate lives in the capital or its immediate suburbs. The city's cost structure benefits from two key developments: the enormous housing supply created by World Cup construction, which has kept rents competitive even as the economy has grown, and government subsidies on electricity and water through Kahramaa, which keep utility bills modest by regional standards. Housing remains the single largest expense for most expatriates, followed by education costs for families and food. This guide provides current 2026 pricing across all major expense categories, drawn from official tariff schedules, property portal data, and retail market surveys, to help you budget accurately before and during your Qatar assignment.</p>

{qatarCostOfLiving.cities.map((city) => (
<>
<h2>{city.name} Cost Breakdown</h2>
<h3>Housing</h3>
<div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto mb-4">
<table class="w-full text-sm"><thead><tr class="bg-teal-600 text-white"><th class="px-3 py-2 text-left rounded-tl-lg">Type</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">Min (QAR)</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">Max (QAR)</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right">EUR Equiv.</th><th class="px-3 py-2 text-right rounded-tr-lg">USD Equiv.</th></tr></thead>
<tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">Studio</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.studioApartment.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.studioApartment.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.min / 3.64).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.studioApartment.max / 3.64).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">1 Bedroom</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.oneBedroom.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.oneBedroom.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.min / 3.64).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.oneBedroom.max / 3.64).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">2 Bedroom</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.twoBedroom.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.twoBedroom.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.min / 3.64).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.twoBedroom.max / 3.64).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
<tr><td class="px-3 py-2">Family Villa</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.familyVilla.min.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">{city.housing.familyVilla.max.toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">€{Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}</td><td class="px-3 py-2 text-right tabular-nums">${Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.min / 3.64).toLocaleString()}-${Math.round(city.housing.familyVilla.max / 3.64).toLocaleString()}</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
</div>
<h3>Food and Groceries</h3>
<p>Monthly groceries for a household: QAR {city.food.groceriesMonthly.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.food.groceriesMonthly.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.food.groceriesMonthly.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.food.groceriesMonthly.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}). Budget dining: QAR {city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.min}-{city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.max} (~€{Math.round(city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.food.mealBudgetRestaurant.max * 0.25)}). Mid-range restaurant: QAR {city.food.mealMidRange.min}-{city.food.mealMidRange.max} (~€{Math.round(city.food.mealMidRange.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.food.mealMidRange.max * 0.25)}). Al Meera, LuLu, and Carrefour are the primary supermarket chains for everyday grocery shopping. Imported European and Australian products typically cost 20-40% more than locally produced or regionally sourced alternatives. Shopping at local markets and buying in-season produce from regional suppliers can meaningfully reduce monthly food bills. Qatar's position as a major air freight hub means that fresh produce, dairy, and meat are imported daily from around the world, ensuring quality and variety even though the country produces only a small fraction of its food domestically.</p>
<h3>Transport</h3>
<p>Doha Metro monthly pass: QAR {city.transport.metroMonthlyPass.amount} (~€{Math.round(city.transport.metroMonthlyPass.amount * 0.25)}). Petrol: QAR {city.transport.gasolinePerLiter.amount}/liter (~€{(city.transport.gasolinePerLiter.amount * 0.25).toFixed(2)}). Taxi and ride-hailing services including Karwa and Uber are widely available throughout the metropolitan area. The Doha Metro, built for the 2022 World Cup and opened in 2019, covers three lines and serves major residential and commercial districts. Despite the metro's modern infrastructure, most expatriates maintain a personal vehicle due to Qatar's compact geography and the affordable cost of fuel. Car insurance runs QAR 1,500 to QAR 3,500 per year, and parking is free in most residential areas and many commercial locations.</p>
<h3>Healthcare</h3>
<p>GP visit: QAR {city.healthcare.gpVisit.min}-{city.healthcare.gpVisit.max} (~€{Math.round(city.healthcare.gpVisit.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.healthcare.gpVisit.max * 0.25)}). Specialist consultation: QAR {city.healthcare.specialistVisit.min}-{city.healthcare.specialistVisit.max} (~€{Math.round(city.healthcare.specialistVisit.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.healthcare.specialistVisit.max * 0.25)}). Employer-provided health insurance is mandatory for all expatriate workers in Qatar. Hamad Medical Corporation operates the public hospital network with 12 facilities, and Sidra Medicine provides specialized women's and children's care. Private options include Al Ahli Hospital and various specialist clinics.</p>
<h3>Education</h3>
<p>International school annual fees: QAR {city.education.internationalSchool.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.education.internationalSchool.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.education.internationalSchool.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.education.internationalSchool.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()}). Nursery: QAR {city.education.nursery.min.toLocaleString()}-{city.education.nursery.max.toLocaleString()} (~€{Math.round(city.education.nursery.min * 0.25).toLocaleString()}-{Math.round(city.education.nursery.max * 0.25).toLocaleString()})/year. Qatar Foundation's Education City hosts branch campuses of Georgetown, Northwestern, Carnegie Mellon, and other internationally recognized universities, providing higher education options within the country.</p>
<h3>Utilities</h3>
<p>Kahramaa (electricity and water): QAR {city.utilities.monthly.min}-{city.utilities.monthly.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.monthly.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.monthly.max * 0.25)})/month. Internet: QAR {city.utilities.internet.min}-{city.utilities.internet.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.internet.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.internet.max * 0.25)}). Mobile: QAR {city.utilities.mobile.min}-{city.utilities.mobile.max} (~€{Math.round(city.utilities.mobile.min * 0.25)}-{Math.round(city.utilities.mobile.max * 0.25)}). Qatar's utility pricing benefits from government subsidies on residential electricity and water consumption. Air conditioning accounts for approximately 60% of electricity costs during the summer months of May through October.</p>
</>
))}

<h2>Budgeting Strategies for Qatar</h2>
<p>Disciplined expatriates in Qatar routinely save 30% to 40% of their gross income, and some achieve savings rates approaching 50% by making strategic lifestyle choices. The most impactful decision is housing. Choosing accommodation in areas like Al Wakrah or Al Khor instead of The Pearl or West Bay can reduce monthly rent by 30% to 50%, saving QAR 2,000 to QAR 4,000 per month without sacrificing basic comfort. Many of these outlying areas are now connected to the Doha Metro, which means the commute trade-off is far less significant than it was before the metro opened.</p>

<p>Grocery shopping at Al Meera and LuLu rather than premium outlets like Monoprix saves 15% to 25% on the monthly food bill. Cooking at home rather than dining out regularly can save an additional QAR 1,000 to QAR 2,000 per month. Using the Doha Metro for daily commuting costs QAR 100 per month versus QAR 600 to QAR 1,000 or more for car ownership expenses including fuel, insurance, and maintenance. Many employers in Qatar provide furnished accommodation or generous housing allowances that can eliminate or dramatically reduce the largest single expense category. Building a financial buffer of three to six months' living expenses before arriving is advisable, as initial setup costs including security deposits, furniture for unfurnished apartments, and vehicle purchase or lease can total QAR 15,000 to QAR 30,000.</p>

<h2>Monthly Budget Examples</h2>
<p>A single professional living in Al Sadd might budget as follows: rent QAR 4,000, utilities QAR 250, groceries QAR 1,000, dining out QAR 800, transport QAR 500, mobile phone QAR 150, gym membership QAR 200, and miscellaneous expenses QAR 400, totaling approximately QAR 7,300 per month. On a salary of QAR 12,000, this leaves monthly savings of QAR 4,700, representing a savings rate of approximately 39%. Annually, that is QAR 56,400 saved, entirely tax-free.</p>

<p>A family of four in a two-bedroom apartment in Lusail might spend: rent QAR 7,000, utilities QAR 400, groceries QAR 1,800, school fees averaged monthly QAR 2,500, transport QAR 700, dining and entertainment QAR 1,200, mobile and internet QAR 400, and miscellaneous QAR 600, totaling approximately QAR 14,600 per month. On a combined household income of QAR 25,000, the family saves QAR 10,400 monthly. None of these amounts carry a VAT surcharge, which saves approximately QAR 700 monthly versus UAE rates or QAR 2,100 monthly versus Saudi Arabia's 15% rate.</p>

<h2>How Qatar Compares to UAE and Saudi Arabia</h2>
<p>Qatar occupies a middle ground in Gulf cost-of-living comparisons. Doha is cheaper than Dubai but somewhat more expensive than Riyadh. However, the zero-VAT policy is Qatar's most powerful cost advantage, effectively saving households 5% to 15% on all spending compared to the UAE and Saudi Arabia. Housing in Doha benefits from the large apartment supply created by World Cup construction, keeping rental markets competitive. Groceries are priced similarly across all three countries since the majority of food is imported regionally.</p>

<p>The areas where Qatar excels most are: no consumption tax on any purchase, affordable and modern public transport via the Doha Metro, government-subsidized utility rates through Kahramaa, and unrestricted VoIP calls, which saves approximately QAR 50 per month compared to the UAE where a BOTIM subscription is required for internet calling. The primary area where Qatar is more expensive is entertainment and leisure, where the smaller market means fewer budget options and less competition than Dubai's enormous hospitality industry. For professionals who prioritize maximizing savings and appreciate a focused, compact living environment, Qatar offers the strongest pure financial proposition in the Gulf.</p>

